In the 3D sample, the value of the Voc dropped from 1.07 to 1.02 V within 5000 h. Using the Maxwell–Wagner (MW) effect model21,22, the relation between the accumulated charges and Voc can be discussed. Once the photogenerated excitons dissociate into free electrons and holes, the holes spread in the HTM layer with a time of "trh" and the electrons spread in the electron transport layer (ETL) with a time of "tre" and thus produce the voltage Voc. Then, excess charge carriers accumulate at the interfaces due to the difference in dielectric relaxation times of the holes and electrons, which express their spreading times in a fashion as Qs = Jsc(trh − tre), (positive current Jsc is defined as that flows from FTO to Au in the solar cell). This phenomenon is called the MW effect, which describes the charge accumulation at the two different materials' interface. In other words, excess carriers accumulate at the interface when the carrier spreading times in the two adjacent materials are different. The electrons accumulate if the (trh<tre\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
